## Working Capital Management

This presentation focuses on managing the day-to-day financial operations of a business.

- Nature and purpose of working capital
- Inventory management
- Trade receivables management
- Trade payables management
- Cash management

## The Working Capital Cycle

Working capital management involves optimizing the cash operating cycle:

```{mermaid}
flowchart LR
    A[Cash] --> B[Inventory]
    B --> C[Accounts Receivable]
    C --> D[Cash]
    E[Accounts Payable] -.-> A
```

## Working Capital Components

The main components of working capital include:

1. **Current assets**:
   - Cash and cash equivalents
   - Accounts receivable
   - Inventory
   - Short-term investments

2. **Current liabilities**:
   - Accounts payable
   - Short-term borrowings
   - Current portion of long-term debt
   - Accrued expenses

## Inventory Management

Effective inventory management balances costs and benefits:

- **Economic Order Quantity (EOQ) model**:
  - Calculates optimal order quantity
  - Minimizes total inventory costs

- **Just-in-Time (JIT) approach**:
  - Reduces inventory holding costs
  - Requires reliable suppliers

## Receivables Management

Managing trade receivables involves:

- Credit policy decisions
- Credit terms and discounts
- Credit evaluation procedures
- Monitoring outstanding receivables
- Collection procedures
- Factoring and invoice discounting 